<HEADLINE>
CYCLISTS BREAKING TRAFFIC RULES LIABLE TO FINES FROM SEPT. 1
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei, May 14 (CNA) 05/14/07  21:00:12 (By Han Nai-kuo)
</P>
<P>
Bicycle riders will be liable to fines of up to NT$600 (US$18)
from Sept. 1 if they commit serious traffic offenses, officials
of the Taipei city government's Department of Transportation said
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The officials said fines will be imposed for running red lights,
riding in the fast lane, cutting across the fast lane, or moving
against the traffic direction.
</P>
<P>
They added that when passing through a crosswalk, cyclists should
yield to pedestrians and will be held responsible if their
failure to yield the right of way causes injury to a pedestrian.
</P>
<P>
The officials also urged cyclists to wear crash helmets, noting
that more than 45 percent of injured bike riders suffer head
injuries.
</P>
